Nodules are the most severe form of acne. Nodules are large painful lesions that can be filled with pus (cystic nodules).

Acne is caused by a combination of factors acting on sebaceous (oil) glands and hair follicles in the skin. Together the oil gland and hair follicle form a channel that secretes oil. If too much oil is produced, oil and dead skin cells can clog the channel and become infected with bacteria. The presence of the bacteria causes the area to become inflamed, resulting in a raised pink bump (pimple) on the surface of the skin.

Factors that increase a patient&#8217s risk of developing acne include hormonal changes, a genetic predisposition (family history) of acne, and oily substances coming in contact with skin. Other factors don&#8217t directly cause acne, but can make it worse, including vigorous scrubbing of the inflamed area, wearing clothing or gear that puts pressure on the skin (like backpacks, helmets, or sports equipment), humidity, and stress.

Cleanse the intended insertion site with antiseptic and allow the antiseptic to dry for 30 seconds. The antiseptic should never be wiped off, but rather allowed to air dry to ensure skin antisepsis. Do not re-touch the area after cleansing with antiseptic.

Intravenous (IV) cannulas are used to administer medications or fluids directly into the bloodstream.

IV cannulas come in several different sizes. The sizes can be easily identified by color. Consider the size of the patient and the clinical situation when choosing a cannula size.

After locating the desired vein and selecting the appropriate IV size, insert the IV with the needle tip bevel-up.
bookmarks.title: IV Insertion

bookmarks.author: BioDigital
bookmarks.description:
In a normal eye, light rays enter the eye through the cornea and are filtered through the pupil to the lens.

The lens is a flexible structure that changes shape in order to focus images on the back of the retina.

Once focused on the retina, the retina processes the image and converts it into nerve signals that can be perceived by the brain.
bookmarks.title: Sight: Sensory Pathway

bookmarks.author: BioDigital
bookmarks.description:
The breasts are mounds of fat and glandular tissue in the front of the chest. Men and women have similar breast tissue during childhood, but sex-specific hormones initiate female breast development during puberty.  During adulthood, female breasts have a well-developed glandular structure that is responsible for milk production. 

Breast cancer is caused by the uncontrolled growth of abnormal cells in the breast. While it can originate from any cell type, the most common forms of breast cancer arise from the lining cells of the lactiferous ducts or lobules. 

The progression of breast cancer is divided into stages based on the size of the tumor, the involvement of lymph nodes, and the metastasis to other parts of the body.
bookmarks.title: Breast Cancer

bookmarks.author: BioDigital
bookmarks.description:
Migraine is a neurological disorder characterized by recurring, episodic headaches. 

The most common migraine symptom is unilateral, pulsating head pain. Accompanying symptoms can include nausea, vomiting, irritability, attention deficits, and increased sensitivity to light, sound, and other non-painful stimuli. 

Although migraine is a relatively common disorder, the mechanisms that cause migraines are not well understood.

One of the major contributors to pain in migraine is thought to be peripheral sensitization (PS). PS is believed to occur when branches of the trigeminal nerve are stimulated. This stimulation typically occurs near the forehead, paranasal sinuses (air-filled spaces near the nose), and the temporomandibular joint.
bookmarks.title: Migraine

bookmarks.author: BioDigital
bookmarks.description:
The heart is a muscular organ located in the midline of the thoracic cavity. Often described as a &#8220pump,&#8221 the heart is responsible for receiving deoxygenated blood, recycling it through the lungs, and supplying oxygenated blood to the body. 

The interior of the heart contains four chambers: two atria (upper chambers) and two ventricles (lower chambers). The atria and ventricles are separated by valves. The tricuspid valve separates the right atrium from the right ventricle, and the mitral valve separates the left atrium from the left ventricle. Valves permit blood to flow into the ventricles, and prevent the backflow of blood into the atria. Two other valves include the pulmonary valve, which permits blood to flow into the pulmonary artery from the right ventricle, and the aortic valve, which permits blood to flow into the aorta from the left ventricle.

Features in the atria include the pectinate muscles, which are ridges of muscle in right atrium, and the fossa ovalis, which is an oval depression visible in the wall between the atria. The fossa ovalis is a remnant of the foramen ovale--an embryological shunt between the atria that closes shortly after birth. 

In the ventricles, tendinous strands called chordae tendinae ("heart strings") extend from the tricuspid and mitral valves to papillary muscles. Columns of muscle called trabeculae carnae extend across the base of the ventricles, enabling the ventricles to contract uniformly. 

The right and left ventricles have muscular walls and are separated by a thick interventricular septum. The left ventricle has the thickest walls, since it needs to generate enough force to pump blood out of the aorta to the rest of the body.
bookmarks.title: Internal Features of the Heart: Right Atrium

bookmarks.description:
The head is the most superior region of the body. It serves as the "control center" of consciousness and contains the brain and bones of the skull, the muscles of facial expression, and special sensory organs.

The neck is the region between the head and trunk. It serves as a passageway for vital vessels and structures, such as the carotid arteries, jugular veins, trachea, and esophagus. It also houses the thyroid gland.
